734
01:14:28,840 --> 01:14:32,800
first step of like, okay, here's a way to move 
forward. Can you just talk about that approach?

735
01:14:32,800 --> 01:14:37,640
So, for me, strategy, this thing called 
strategy, with people, oh my God, oh my God,  

736
01:14:37,640 --> 01:14:44,040
how am I going to do strategy? Whatever. I just 
think of it as a problem solving tool. And what  

737
01:14:44,040 --> 01:14:51,720
problem should you attempt to solve? You should 
attempt to solve something where your current  

738
01:14:51,720 --> 01:14:58,840
outcomes that you're getting are lower than the 
outcomes you wish you were getting. That's what  

739
01:14:58,840 --> 01:15:05,000
I call a gap. There's a gap between those two. And 
you should just conceptualize it as, your current  

740
01:15:05,000 --> 01:15:11,600
outcomes are a natural result of all the choices 
you've made interacting with the competitive  

741
01:15:11,600 --> 01:15:18,160
environment. And so, you should reasonably assume 
that probably those outcomes aren't going to get  

742
01:15:18,160 --> 01:15:25,400
a whole lot better, because they are the way 
they are for a good reason. So, you're going to  

743
01:15:25,400 --> 01:15:31,280
need to make a different set of choices to make 
that gap go away. That's what I would work on. 

744
01:15:31,280 --> 01:15:35,640
I would just ask the question, what is 
the single most painful gap currently  

745
01:15:35,640 --> 01:15:42,080
that I'm facing? Customers used to do this, and 
they're doing this, I can't find this kind of  

746
01:15:42,920 --> 01:15:49,480
resources, our distribution channel has abandoned 
us... Whatever is the most painful thing,  

747
01:15:49,480 --> 01:15:55,600
and then just tackle that. And say, what 
different choices could I make? And I'd say,  

748
01:15:55,600 --> 01:16:01,840
use my cascade. Could I change where I'm playing? 
Could I change how I'm winning? Could I change my  

749
01:16:01,840 --> 01:16:09,560
capabilities? Could I change my manage systems, in 
order to achieve a different aspiration? And so,  

750
01:16:09,560 --> 01:16:16,160
don't try to solve the problems of the world, 
or even all the problems of your company,  

751
01:16:16,160 --> 01:16:21,640
that's perfection. Betterment is making that gap 
go away. And guess what happens if you make that  

752
01:16:21,640 --> 01:16:27,320
gap go away? You can turn your attention to the 
next gap, and the next gap, and the next gap. 

753
01:16:28,760 --> 01:16:35,960
And if you do that all the time, you're always 
working on the next gap, the next... They'll  

754
01:16:35,960 --> 01:16:42,960
get smaller and smaller over time. I don't know 
if this is a great analogy, but I was dean of  

755
01:16:42,960 --> 01:16:48,040
a business school for 15 years, the guy who won 
the professor of the year award more times than  

756
01:16:48,040 --> 01:16:52,840
anybody else, and did it sort of teaching 
tough courses, often executive MBA courses,  

757
01:16:52,840 --> 01:17:04,520
and the like, had a simple formula for doing 
it. Which is, he taught second-year courses,  

758
01:17:04,520 --> 01:17:10,360
and second-year courses happened to be 13 two hour 
lectures, or sessions, [inaudible 01:17:10] or  

759
01:17:10,360 --> 01:17:18,520
another. He just polled the students on what they 
thought of each session as they went along, and  

760
01:17:18,520 --> 01:17:24,840
regardless of the reason, regardless of anything 
else, simply chopped number 13 every year. 

761
01:17:26,640 --> 01:17:33,160
Because in some sense, it's the biggest gap, 
the gap between what the customers, students,  

762
01:17:33,160 --> 01:17:40,120
wished for, and were getting. And he would just 
replace it with something. He would try something  

763
01:17:40,120 --> 01:17:46,200
else, and replace it with that. And you'd say, 
and that gets you professor of the year every  

764
01:17:46,200 --> 01:17:54,040
year? And the answer is yes, betterment. 
Because if you're teaching for 25 years  

765
01:17:54,600 --> 01:18:02,280
and you just keep doing that every year, every 
year, the course keeps getting better and better  

766
01:18:02,280 --> 01:18:13,200
and better and better and better and better. So, 
betterment, it doesn't make purists feel awesome,  

767
01:18:13,200 --> 01:18:21,440
but I'm not here to make purists feel 
awesome, I'm here to help people get better.

768
01:18:21,440 --> 01:18:24,240
This makes me think about your water 
metaphor too, of just water eventually  

769
01:18:24,240 --> 01:18:27,920
finding a way through. [inaudible 01:18:26] 
iterating, [inaudible 01:18:27] things better.

770
01:18:27,920 --> 01:18:31,680
Yeah, lots of what I think 
about in strategy is natural,  

771
01:18:31,680 --> 01:18:36,640
if you will. I try to ask, how 
does the world generally operate,  

772
01:18:36,640 --> 01:18:42,560
and is what we're doing consistent with the 
way the world generally operates or not?

773
01:18:42,560 --> 01:18:46,480
Roger, this was so much fun, we covered 
everything I was hoping we'd get through.  

774
01:18:46,480 --> 01:18:49,000
I think we're going to help a lot of 
people with the way they think about  

775
01:18:49,000 --> 01:18:51,600
strategy. Is there anything else you 
wanted to just leave listeners with,  

776
01:18:51,600 --> 01:18:58,560
or say before we wrap up and let you go? We 
covered a lot, so there may not be anything left.

777
01:18:58,560 --> 01:19:03,160
Well, on strategy, there's one piece 
of advice I'd say. People often ask  

778
01:19:03,160 --> 01:19:10,720
me about people who are natural strategists, 
or they say, I'm not naturally good at that,  

779
01:19:10,720 --> 01:19:18,760
I'm more of an operational guy or gal. And what 
I tell them is, I have never met this mythical  

780
01:19:18,760 --> 01:19:25,040
beast called a great natural strategist. And they 
often throw back in my face, Lafley. They say,  

781
01:19:25,040 --> 01:19:34,360
look, Lafley, he was known as a strategy genius. 
And I say, yeah, but when I interviewed him in  

782
01:19:34,360 --> 01:19:41,120
depth about his background, for a paper I was 
writing, what I discovered was when he was in  

783
01:19:41,120 --> 01:19:49,320
the Navy, as a whatever, I don't know, probably 
25-year-old in the Navy, he had a job where he had  

784
01:19:49,320 --> 01:19:54,280
to think about strategy, and was testing things 
out, and doing things, and the like. And then,  

785
01:19:54,280 --> 01:20:03,760
I realized that he had been practicing strategy 
for decades before he became the CEO, decades. 

786
01:20:04,280 --> 01:20:11,960
And so, he just had more reps when he became 
CEO than almost anybody else that I've ever met.  

787
01:20:11,960 --> 01:20:18,600
There's another guy, [inaudible 01:20:15], ex-CEO, 
now he's gone on to a higher level of Lego brand  

788
01:20:18,600 --> 01:20:29,000
group, would be similar. So, great strategists 
that I have met have all one thing in common. They  

789
01:20:29,000 --> 01:20:38,800
just practice. And anybody, there's no such thing 
as a person who is willing to practice strategy,  

790
01:20:38,800 --> 01:20:45,360
who will end up saying, I'm operational, 
I don't do strategy well. Which links to  

791
01:20:45,360 --> 01:20:52,640
our last thing about betterment. Just work on 
making different choices to solve problems.  

792
01:20:52,640 --> 01:20:57,280
Not problems that I say, I'm not going to define 
your gap, it's one that you feel in your heart,  

793
01:20:57,280 --> 01:21:03,120
I wish this were better. Work on it, if you 
do that, you'll be a great strategist. So,  

794
01:21:03,120 --> 01:21:12,320
be encouraged, don't be discouraged. And the 
worst thing to do is to wait. People say,  

795
01:21:12,320 --> 01:21:18,160
well, I've got all these operational concerns 
right now, and then I'll get to strategy later.  

796
01:21:18,160 --> 01:21:22,160
You'll never amount to anything. Nobody 
who says that ever amounts to anything.

797
